00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:18.850 align:middle line:84%
But nevertheless, the question
asks about important concepts.

00:01:18.850 --> 00:01:20.340 align:middle line:90%
So let me read the first one.

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:22.560 align:middle line:84%
Draw a consumption
set which consists

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:27.210 align:middle line:84%
of discrete number of points
argue that th set is not convex

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:30.720 align:middle line:84%
and then show how
lotteries which put mass

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:34.620 align:middle line:84%
on these discrete points,
transforms the consumption set

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:36.780 align:middle line:90%
into something convex.

00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:41.160 align:middle line:84%
So there's two sentences there,
effectively two questions.

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:42.890 align:middle line:90%
Could I get a volunteer, please?

00:01:42.890 --> 00:01:46.770 align:middle line:90%


00:01:46.770 --> 00:01:48.190 align:middle line:90%
So you can't actually draw it.

00:01:48.190 --> 00:01:52.260 align:middle line:84%
Can you describe
a consumption set?

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:55.770 align:middle line:90%
Maybe these words suffice.

00:01:55.770 --> 00:01:58.590 align:middle line:84%
Try to describe, in words,
a consumption set which

00:01:58.590 --> 00:02:00.390 align:middle line:84%
contains a discrete
number of points

00:02:00.390 --> 00:02:04.790 align:middle line:90%
and tell me why it's not convex.

00:02:04.790 --> 00:02:05.980 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:10.190 align:middle line:84%
So I think we
discussed this earlier.

00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:14.590 align:middle line:84%
But one consumption
set was consuming lunch

00:02:14.590 --> 00:02:17.860 align:middle line:84%
in New York at noon
versus consuming lunch

00:02:17.860 --> 00:02:19.930 align:middle line:90%
in Washington, DC at noon.

00:02:19.930 --> 00:02:21.190 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: That's true.

00:02:21.190 --> 00:02:23.440 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So that would be
a discrete consumption set.

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:26.050 align:middle line:84%
And since you
can't consume lunch

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:28.540 align:middle line:84%
in a mixture of
those two cities,

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:31.000 align:middle line:84%
then the consumption
is not convex.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.880 align:middle line:84%
But if you had a sum
probability of eating lunch

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:37.390 align:middle line:84%
in either location, then
you could have a probability

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:40.240 align:middle line:90%
between zero and one.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:43.480 align:middle line:84%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: And
how would you draw it?

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:48.038 align:middle line:90%


00:02:48.038 --> 00:02:50.330 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So for the original
discrete consumption set,

00:02:50.330 --> 00:02:52.360 align:middle line:90%
you'd just be two points.

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:54.160 align:middle line:84%
I think one of those
points would be one,

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:57.160 align:middle line:84%
zero and one of those
points will be zero, one.

00:02:57.160 --> 00:02:59.680 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Good.

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:01.300 align:middle line:90%
And can you imagine how--

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:05.320 align:middle line:84%
I'll help in a second
if it's not clear--

00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:07.600 align:middle line:84%
can you imagine how you
would be able to convert

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:12.760 align:middle line:84%
that set into something that
is convex, using the lottery?

00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:15.972 align:middle line:84%
Is there something you
could draw to depict it?

00:03:15.972 --> 00:03:18.430 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If you just sort of
drew a line between those two

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:20.890 align:middle line:84%
points, like your
location, instead

00:03:20.890 --> 00:03:25.030 align:middle line:84%
of doing how many lunches
you eat at DC and New York,

00:03:25.030 --> 00:03:28.960 align:middle line:84%
you could do the probability
that you eat at DC or New York.

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:30.700 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Exactly.

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:34.870 align:middle line:84%
So now we have a line
running on the diagonal

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:37.510 align:middle line:90%
from one, zero to zero one.

00:03:37.510 --> 00:03:39.410 align:middle line:90%
The end points are still there.

00:03:39.410 --> 00:03:41.350 align:middle line:84%
Those are lotteries
that are degenerate.

00:03:41.350 --> 00:03:45.580 align:middle line:84%
They're putting probability
one on each of the endpoints.

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:49.360 align:middle line:84%
An intermediate lottery, a
non-trivial lottery, say,

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:54.410 align:middle line:84%
halfway between, would
put probability 1/2 on--

00:03:54.410 --> 00:03:58.880 align:middle line:84%
would be distance 1/2 to
one, zero and distance 1/4

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:00.710 align:middle line:90%
to zero, one.

00:04:00.710 --> 00:04:03.630 align:middle line:84%
And that represents an
equal weighted probability.

00:04:03.630 --> 00:04:07.810 align:middle line:84%
And you can inch closer to
one endpoint or the other.

00:04:07.810 --> 00:04:10.990 align:middle line:84%
Those are still
non-degenerate lotteries.

00:04:10.990 --> 00:04:13.330 align:middle line:84%
So a lottery, when you
put a point in there,

00:04:13.330 --> 00:04:17.589 align:middle line:90%
represents the weights.

00:04:17.589 --> 00:04:19.339 align:middle line:84%
But yes, your
answer was perfect.

00:04:19.339 --> 00:04:21.310 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:04:21.310 --> 00:04:22.315 align:middle line:90%
Questions about that?

00:04:22.315 --> 00:04:25.900 align:middle line:90%


00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:28.170 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:32.340 align:middle line:84%
What does risk aversion imply
about the consumer's utility

00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:34.800 align:middle line:90%
function?

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:37.470 align:middle line:90%
Again, I'll take volunteers.

00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:39.690 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If you're
risk averse, then you

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:42.610 align:middle line:84%
have diminishing marginal
utility of income.

00:04:42.610 --> 00:04:47.220 align:middle line:84%
So the utility function
should be concave.

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:48.490 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Good.

00:04:48.490 --> 00:04:49.555 align:middle line:90%
Strictly or weakly?

00:04:49.555 --> 00:04:52.810 align:middle line:90%


00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:55.300 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Convex?

00:04:55.300 --> 00:04:56.710 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Let me repeat.

00:04:56.710 --> 00:04:59.890 align:middle line:84%
The question says what
does risk aversion imply

00:04:59.890 --> 00:05:03.080 align:middle line:84%
about the consumer's
utility function.

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:04.810 align:middle line:90%
So your answer, concave, yes.

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:08.290 align:middle line:84%
And I'm asking back, you
mean strictly concave,

00:05:08.290 --> 00:05:11.450 align:middle line:90%
weakly concave.

00:05:11.450 --> 00:05:14.390 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I mean, I think it
would be weakly concave, right?

00:05:14.390 --> 00:05:17.510 align:middle line:84%
Because if you have
a straight line--

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:20.120 align:middle line:84%
or actually would that still
be considered risk averse,

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:24.170 align:middle line:84%
if your utility from
getting a certain value

00:05:24.170 --> 00:05:29.270 align:middle line:84%
is like completely equal
to the utility of having

00:05:29.270 --> 00:05:30.920 align:middle line:90%
that as your expected value?

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:31.340 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: All right.

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:32.000 align:middle line:90%
That's perfect.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:33.030 align:middle line:90%
You figured it out.

00:05:33.030 --> 00:05:36.320 align:middle line:84%
So the answer is we typically
think of risk aversion

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:39.860 align:middle line:84%
to mean strictly
averse to the lottery.

00:05:39.860 --> 00:05:46.010 align:middle line:84%
And hence, the linear case of
the linear utility function,

00:05:46.010 --> 00:05:48.170 align:middle line:84%
or weekly concave
function, but not

00:05:48.170 --> 00:05:51.830 align:middle line:84%
strictly concave, we
call them risk neutral

00:05:51.830 --> 00:05:53.780 align:middle line:90%
and not risk averse.

00:05:53.780 --> 00:05:55.380 align:middle line:90%
But I never said that in class.

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:59.200 align:middle line:90%
So I'm amplifying.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:02.260 align:middle line:84%
But yes, risk aversion
is being risk averse.

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:07.340 align:middle line:84%
Strictly speaking implies
strictly concave utility.

00:06:07.340 --> 00:06:08.750 align:middle line:90%
So perfect, thank you.

00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:14.490 align:middle line:90%


00:06:14.490 --> 00:06:17.660 align:middle line:90%
So one more here.

00:06:17.660 --> 00:06:21.290 align:middle line:84%
This, again, is going to require
you to describe something.

00:06:21.290 --> 00:06:26.480 align:middle line:84%
Combining states and time of
the world, time and states

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:30.140 align:middle line:84%
of the world, what is the
complete commodity space

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:33.590 align:middle line:90%
for a consumer?

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:35.060 align:middle line:84%
And what I'm really
looking for is

00:06:35.060 --> 00:06:39.680 align:middle line:84%
for you to describe to me the
tree of possibilities that we

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:41.900 align:middle line:90%
had on the slide last time.

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:44.810 align:middle line:90%


00:06:44.810 --> 00:06:46.610 align:middle line:84%
And, again, I'll
take volunteers.

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:53.750 align:middle line:90%


00:06:53.750 --> 00:06:56.940 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So this is a tree
that's oriented upwards.

00:06:56.940 --> 00:07:01.730 align:middle line:84%
And so at where time increases
as you go up in this tree.

00:07:01.730 --> 00:07:04.280 align:middle line:84%
As you make a specific
choice at any given time,

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:08.675 align:middle line:84%
you limit your future
options to some specific set,

00:07:08.675 --> 00:07:11.300 align:middle line:84%
and you exclude some others that
are no longer possible for you

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:11.800 align:middle line:90%
to consume.

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:15.510 align:middle line:90%


00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:17.040 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: That's right.

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:22.390 align:middle line:84%
So the tricky part
of it is to remember

00:07:22.390 --> 00:07:26.170 align:middle line:84%
that the state of
the world at any date

00:07:26.170 --> 00:07:29.230 align:middle line:84%
is not just a set of
possible realizations

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:31.330 align:middle line:90%
of the contemporary shock.

00:07:31.330 --> 00:07:35.890 align:middle line:84%
It also includes the history
of shocks, up to and including

00:07:35.890 --> 00:07:38.550 align:middle line:90%
the contemporary date.

00:07:38.550 --> 00:07:41.180 align:middle line:84%
So that's what's going
on with that tree.

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:44.930 align:middle line:90%
You pick a node in the tree.

00:07:44.930 --> 00:07:48.740 align:middle line:84%
It's described not just by
the set of all things that

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:51.730 align:middle line:84%
could have happened
on the current branch,

00:07:51.730 --> 00:07:56.410 align:middle line:84%
but the set of all things that
could possibly have happened up

00:07:56.410 --> 00:07:59.260 align:middle line:90%
to and including that point.

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:02.970 align:middle line:84%
And actually, I made
the comment in class

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:05.460 align:middle line:84%
that one has to consider
whether you're already

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:09.510 align:middle line:84%
at the current date, or
whether you're at date zero,

00:08:09.510 --> 00:08:12.870 align:middle line:84%
imagining what could
happen in the future.

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:14.582 align:middle line:84%
Because if you're at
zero and imagining

00:08:14.582 --> 00:08:16.290 align:middle line:84%
what could happen in
the future, then you

00:08:16.290 --> 00:08:20.100 align:middle line:84%
have to delineate all
possible histories

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:23.890 align:middle line:84%
and all possible states that
can happen in any given date,

00:08:23.890 --> 00:08:27.945 align:middle line:84%
including up through and
including the date in question.

00:08:27.945 --> 00:08:30.860 align:middle line:90%


00:08:30.860 --> 00:08:31.500 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:32.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.169 align:middle line:90%


00:08:35.169 --> 00:08:37.240 align:middle line:84%
So, again, I earmarked
some of these.

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:40.720 align:middle line:84%
I only went through
three of the four.

00:08:40.720 --> 00:08:41.750 align:middle line:90%
That was very helpful.

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:43.570 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:51.730 align:middle line:90%
OK, so the lecture today is--

00:08:51.730 --> 00:08:57.520 align:middle line:84%
so this is on dynamics
and dynamic programming.

00:08:57.520 --> 00:09:00.430 align:middle line:84%
It's going to focus
on this application

00:09:00.430 --> 00:09:03.520 align:middle line:84%
